  <!-- ============ STANDARDS LAYER (charcoal) ============ -->
  <section class="section dark">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-head">
        <span class="label">03 · Always included</span>
        <h2>The standards layer.<br/><em>What keeps the skills working after we leave.</em></h2>
      </div>

      <div class="row-2col asym" style="margin-bottom:48px;">
        <div>
          <p style="font-family:var(--lf-serif);font-style:italic;font-weight:350;font-size:19px;line-height:1.5;color:var(--lf-graphite);">
            A skill without standards underneath is a one-off workflow that breaks in six months.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="prose">
          <p>Most AI consulting ships a workflow and disappears. Within a quarter, the model API changes shape, the prompt drifts, the team that owned it leaves, and the workflow quietly stops getting used. We've watched it happen at companies we've been customers of.</p>
          <p>The standards layer is the layer underneath every skill that lets your team adapt as the AI stack evolves. It's documentation, conventions, tooling, and a wiki — built so a new operator can read it on a flight and pick up where we left off. <strong>It's free in every implementation.</strong> It's also the moat.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="row-list">
        <div class="row">
          <div class="num">LAYER · 01</div>
          <div><h3>The framework library</h3></div>
          <div class="body">Eleven canonical docs that govern <em>how</em> every skill we install operates. Batch architecture (collect → filter → batch-generate → execute, never per-item AI calls). Source-of-truth hierarchy (which data system wins when two disagree). Model selection rules. Browser automation best practices. Tier-evaluation logic. The data-validation library. Plus five more. When a new model lands, your team reads the framework and updates skills accordingly.</div>
          <div class="meta">11 docs</div>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
          <div class="num">LAYER · 02</div>
          <div><h3>Brand &amp; copy standards</h3></div>
          <div class="body">Brand context, voice rules, copy-rules enforcement skill — forked from LF canonical and customized to your business. Becomes the source of truth for everything customer-facing: ad copy, landing pages, email, social, support replies.</div>
          <div class="meta">3 docs + 1 skill</div>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
          <div class="num">LAYER · 03</div>
          <div><h3>Project conventions</h3></div>
          <div class="body">Folder structure, file naming, skill authoring standard, engagement cadence, what gets measured weekly. The conventions that let your team write skill N+1 without us. Modeled on the operating systems we use at Stix and Host Modern.</div>
          <div class="meta">1 doc + scaffolding</div>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
          <div class="num">LAYER · 04</div>
          <div><h3>The wiki</h3></div>
          <div class="body">A local-served HTML hub that organizes every doc, framework, dashboard, and skill spec. Pre-rendered from markdown — opens via file://, no server, no internet. Works on a flight. Anyone on your team can browse the entire operating system from one launch point.</div>
          <div class="meta">Local-first</div>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
          <div class="num">LAYER · 05</div>
          <div><h3>Operating tooling</h3></div>
          <div class="body">The CLAUDE.md context file that auto-loads in any AI session your team runs. The wiki build script (markdown → HTML on every doc edit). The approval queue and run log when a skill produces decisions needing human review. The per-skill runbook your ops person reads at 6am when something breaks.</div>
          <div class="meta">Scripts + state</div>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
          <div class="num">LAYER · 06</div>
          <div><h3>Training</h3></div>
          <div class="body">Two ninety-minute sessions with the team owning the work. One <em>operational</em> — how to monitor, when to intervene, what each runbook covers. One <em>editorial</em> — how to update prompts, how to author the next skill, how to extend the framework library when your business changes.</div>
          <div class="meta">2 sessions</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p style="margin-top:48px;font-family:var(--lf-serif);font-style:italic;font-size:17px;line-height:1.6;color:var(--lf-graphite);max-width:760px;">
        Six layers, free in every implementation. They're the difference between a workflow that runs for a quarter and an operating system that compounds for years.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ HOW IT RUNS ============ -->
  <section class="section rule">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-head">
        <span class="label">04 · How a 90-day implementation runs</span>
        <h2>Twelve weeks.<br/><em>Same shape every time.</em></h2>
      </div>

      <div class="row-list">
        <div class="row">
          <div class="num">Week 0</div>
          <div><h3>Kickoff</h3></div>
          <div class="body">Both operators in the room. We agree in writing on what success looks like at day 90, who gives feedback, what's out of scope. Pinned to your wiki by end of day.</div>
          <div class="meta">1 hour</div>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
          <div class="num">Weeks 1–2</div>
          <div><h3>Read and decide</h3></div>
          <div class="body">We read your stack — APIs, dashboards, Slack history, agency reports, the spreadsheet that's actually how the business runs. We interview operators. End of week two: skills confirmed, order set.</div>
          <div class="meta">Audit</div>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
          <div class="num">Weeks 3–7</div>
          <div><h3>Build and shadow</h3></div>
          <div class="body">Each skill ships in shadow mode first — running parallel to manual processes, outputs to a draft inbox. Shadow surfaces edge cases the briefing missed. Most weeks we're rewriting prompts based on what shadow produced.</div>
          <div class="meta">Build</div>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
          <div class="num">Weeks 8–10</div>
          <div><h3>Live and tune</h3></div>
          <div class="body">Skills go live one at a time. Shadow logs run a week after each go-live. Tuning happens in three places: the prompt, the script, the runbook. The runbook is what a future ops person reads at 6am when something breaks.</div>
          <div class="meta">Launch</div>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
          <div class="num">Weeks 11–12</div>
          <div><h3>Handoff and write-up</h3></div>
          <div class="body">Two 90-minute training sessions — one operational, one editorial. Framework library reviewed against your context. Everything committed to your repo. We hand the keys and step out.</div>
          <div class="meta">Handoff</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

